    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-06-13T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-06-13T16:00:00-05:00" n="293"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d293">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/5268: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-06-13T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 13, 1930—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>193. Your 377, May 28, 5 p.m., paragraph 2. Referring to the Legation’s reports
                    regarding the proposed interference by the northern leaders with the functioning
                    of the Chinese Maritime Customs at Tientsin, the Department has noted with
                    satisfaction that no serious complication appears to have arisen affecting
                    either the conduct of international trade at Tientsin or such rights as American
                    creditors may have in respect to the customs revenues. Referring to your
                    telegram 306, May 5, 8 p.m., last sentence, you are asked to report whether the
                    Commissioner of Customs is at present assessing and collecting customs duties
                    and remitting them to the National Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
